    • Method Detail

      • getInitialHash

        public Hash getInitialHash()
        Getter of the hash of the transaction that the snapshot was "derived" from. In case of the "latest" Snapshot this value will be the hash of the "initial" Snapshot. Note: a snapshot can be modified over time, as we apply the balance changes caused by consecutive transactions, so this value differs from the value returned by SnapshotMetaData.getHash().
        Specified by:
        getInitialHash in interface SnapshotMetaData
        Returns:
        hash of the transaction that the snapshot was "derived" from

      • getSolidEntryPoints

        public java.util.Map<Hash,java.lang.Integer> getSolidEntryPoints()
        Getter for the solid entry points of the snapshot. A solid entry point is a confirmed transaction that had non-orphaned approvers during the time of the snapshot creation and therefore a connection to the most recent part of the tangle. The solid entry points allow us to stop the solidification process without having to go all the way back to the genesis. Note: Nodes that do not use local snapshots will only have one solid entry point (the NULL_HASH).
        Specified by:
        getSolidEntryPoints in interface SnapshotMetaData
        Returns:
        map with the transaction hashes associated to their milestone index

      • setSolidEntryPoints

        public void setSolidEntryPoints(java.util.Map<Hash,java.lang.Integer> solidEntryPoints)
        Setter for the solid entry points of this snapshot. A solid entry point is a confirmed transaction that had non-orphaned approvers during the time of the snapshot creation and therefore a connection to the most recent part of the tangle. The solid entry points allow us to stop the solidification process without having to go all the way back to the genesis. Note: Nodes that do not use local snapshots should only have one solid entry point (the NULL_HASH).
        Specified by:
        setSolidEntryPoints in interface SnapshotMetaData
        Parameters:
        solidEntryPoints - map with the transaction hashes associated to their milestone index

      • hasSolidEntryPoint

        public boolean hasSolidEntryPoint(Hash solidEntrypoint)
        This method checks if a given transaction is a solid entry point. It simply performs a member check on the value returned by SnapshotMetaData.getSolidEntryPoints() and therefore is a utility method that makes it easier to check a single transaction. A solid entry point is a confirmed transaction that had non-orphaned approvers during the time of the snapshot creation and therefore a connection to the most recent part of the tangle. The solid entry points allow us to stop the solidification process without having to go all the way back to the genesis.
        Specified by:
        hasSolidEntryPoint in interface SnapshotMetaData
        Parameters:
        solidEntrypoint - transaction hash that shall be checked
        Returns:
        true if the hash is a solid entry point and false otherwise

      • getSolidEntryPointIndex

        public int getSolidEntryPointIndex(Hash solidEntrypoint)
        Returns the index of the milestone that was responsible for confirming the transaction that is now a solid entry point. A solid entry point is a confirmed transaction that had non-orphaned approvers during the time of the snapshot creation and therefore a connection to the most recent part of the tangle. The solid entry points allow us to stop the solidification process without having to go all the way back to the genesis.
        Specified by:
        getSolidEntryPointIndex in interface SnapshotMetaData
        Parameters:
        solidEntrypoint - transaction hash of the solid entry point
        Returns:
        index of the milestone that once confirmed the solid entry point or null if the given transaction is no solid entry point

      • getSeenMilestones

        public java.util.Map<Hash,java.lang.Integer> getSeenMilestones()
        Getter for the seen milestones. Note: Since new nodes use local snapshot files as a way to bootstrap their database, we store the hashes of all milestones that have been following the snapshot in its meta data. This allows these nodes to immediately start requesting the missing milestones without having to discover them one by one, which massively increases the sync speed of new nodes.
        Specified by:
        getSeenMilestones in interface SnapshotMetaData
        Returns:
        map of milestone transaction hashes associated to their milestone index

      • setSeenMilestones

        public void setSeenMilestones(java.util.Map<Hash,java.lang.Integer> seenMilestones)

Note: Since new nodes use local snapshot files as a way to bootstrap their database, we store the hashes of all milestones that have been following the snapshot in its meta data. This allows these nodes to immediately start requesting the missing milestones without having to discover them one by one, which massively increases the sync speed of new nodes.
        Specified by:
        setSeenMilestones in interface SnapshotMetaData
        Parameters:
        seenMilestones - map of milestone transaction hashes associated to their milestone index

      • update

        public void update(SnapshotMetaData newMetaData)
        Replaces the meta data values of this instance with the values of another meta data object. This can for example be used to "reset" the meta data after a failed modification attempt (while being able to keep the same instance).
        Specified by:

        Parameters:
